00:17:18,178 --> 00:17:19,700
why a man is dead.

251
00:17:20,047 --> 00:17:22,120
You want to come at me,
you come at me straight.

252
00:17:22,157 --> 00:17:24,901
You want it straight?
I did not see a gun!

253
00:17:25,906 --> 00:17:27,202
A ngel.

254
00:17:27,605 --> 00:17:29,251
I need to talk to you.

255
00:17:30,797 --> 00:17:32,583
Help me out, man.

256
00:17:47,325 --> 00:17:49,342
- Is that Joe?
- Must be.

257
00:17:53,595 --> 00:17:57,310
It's weird,
but he looks a little bit like you...

258
00:17:57,485 --> 00:17:59,021
But not really.

259
00:17:59,448 --> 00:18:01,932
Those seem to be the only
pictures in the house.

260
00:18:02,167 --> 00:18:07,012
There's no family
or kids' photos.

261
00:18:07,858 --> 00:18:09,201
Lonely.

262
00:18:17,667 --> 00:18:20,721
- Dexter. Hi.
- Hey.

263
00:18:20,868 --> 00:18:21,893
Surprise.

264
00:18:25,495 --> 00:18:28,271
I know you can't
ask for my help, but

265
00:18:28,456 --> 00:18:30,710
it's my duty to, you know...

266
00:18:32,097 --> 00:18:35,861
Help while you deal
with old wounds...

267
00:18:36,047 --> 00:18:38,533
Or wha-- Jesus.
Whatever. I'm here.

268
00:18:38,606 --> 00:18:39,700
So it appears.

269
00:18:39,805 --> 00:18:42,231
And this is Rudy.

270
00:18:46,545 --> 00:18:49,221
I've waited a long
time to meet you.

271
00:18:50,426 --> 00:18:52,433
And you must be Rita.

272
00:18:53,345 --> 00:18:54,592
Hi.

273
00:18:55,588 --> 00:18:58,951
He came here for me --
For the both of us.

274
00:18:59,698 --> 00:19:01,001
Isn't he great?

275
00:19:09,606 --> 00:19:11,852
A lot of work to
pack all this up.

276
00:19:11,958 --> 00:19:14,853
Even with the four of us,
it'll take us the whole weekend.

277
00:19:14,865 --> 00:19:17,260
The whole weekend?
Where should I put our stuff?

278
00:19:18,677 --> 00:19:22,201
It's too eerie,
sleeping in a dead man's house.

279
00:19:22,348 --> 00:19:24,313
I saw a Motel 6 on the way in.

280
00:19:24,497 --> 00:19:26,610
We could stay here
and save the money.

281
00:19:26,797 --> 00:19:28,150
I mean, it is late,

282
00:19:28,248 --> 00:19:30,502
and we'd probably get more
packing done if we stayed here.

283
00:19:30,905 --> 00:19:32,553
It's up to you, Dex.

284
00:19:32,608 --> 00:19:34,233
Just say the word.

285
00:19:36,435 --> 00:19:38,593
As long as you don't
mind the sofa bed.

286
00:19:40,118 --> 00:19:42,613
Okay, I'll go look
for some clean sheets.

287
00:19:50,567 --> 00:19:53,623
<i>How did a death turn
into a couples' weekend?</i>

288
00:19:59,675 --> 00:20:02,591
<i>Luckily, I get up earlier
than normal people.</i>

289
00:20:03,375 --> 00:20:04,451
Coffee?

290
00:20:07,227 --> 00:20:08,572
Thanks.

291
00:20:08,895 --> 00:20:10,561
I've got to hit the morgue.

292
00:20:13,566 --> 00:20:15,022
Want company?

293
00:20:16,438 --> 00:20:17,650
No.

294
00:20:18,485 --> 00:20:21,772
- Thank you, though.
- It's private.

295
00:20:22,478 --> 00:20:23,590
I get it.

296
00:20:34,146 --> 00:20:36,853
I gave Joe a physical once a year,
like clockwork,

297
00:20:36,965 --> 00:20:39,930
so no history of heart disease,
but it happens.

298
00:20:40,076 --> 00:20:41,191
It appears so.

299
00:20:41,326 --> 00:20:44,022
We were about to send him to a
crematorium when we found you.

300
00:20:44,106 --> 00:20:45,850
We thought

301
00:20:45,987 --> 00:20:48,931
his son should have a chance
to pay his last respects.

302
00:20:49,066 --> 00:20:50,473
I'm not his son.

303
00:20:51,306 --> 00:20:53,933
Estrangement in a
family is a shame, but

304
00:20:54,626 --> 00:20:56,881
death is the great unifier.

305
00:21:35,788 --> 00:21:38,312
That's an interesting tattoo.

306
00:21:38,767 --> 00:21:41,010
Joe said he picked
that up in Nam.

307
00:21:41,248 --> 00:21:43,400
You can be proud.
He was a patriot.

308
00:21:43,686 --> 00:21:46,222
Uh, perhaps he was
also an ex-convict.

309
00:21:46,406 --> 00:21:48,470
- Excuse me?
- It's a prison tattoo.

310
00:21:48,656 --> 00:21:50,602
It's done with a pen
and ballpoint ink.

311
00:21:51,178 --> 00:21:54,650
It's three or four decades old,
judging by the fade.

312
00:21:55,166 --> 00:21:57,161
Son, I knew Joe. He
was no ex-convict.

313
00:21:57,165 --> 00:21:59,180
He was a good man,

314
00:21:59,307 --> 00:22:00,470
a quiet man,

315
00:22:00,807 --> 00:22:03,722
and a damn good bowler.

316
00:22:05,606 --> 00:22:07,350
How'd you determine
cardiac arrest?

317
00:22:07,478 --> 00:22:09,760
Was there damage to
the coronary artery?

318
00:22:10,826 --> 00:22:12,840
It's, uh,
professional curiosity.

319
00:22:13,078 --> 00:22:14,820
I work in forensics,
down in Miami.

320
00:22:15,118 --> 00:22:16,090
I see.

321
00:22:16,646 --> 00:22:21,442
Well, uh, I found microaneurisms
in the retinas.

322
00:22:21,638 --> 00:22:24,451
It's common with seizures
during a heart attack.

323
00:22:24,636 --> 00:22:27,172
It's also a sign of
diabetic retinopathy.

324
00:22:28,485 --> 00:22:30,743
Son, I may be a
small-town doctor,

325
00:22:30,786 --> 00:22:33,031
but I know a heart
attack when I see one.

326
00:22:35,005 --> 00:22:37,203
Who knows what caused it --

327
00:22:37,425 --> 00:22:38,602
Stress,

328
00:22:38,707 --> 00:22:40,562
inactivity...

329
00:22:41,277 --> 00:22:42,921
French fries --

330
00:22:44,078 --> 00:22:46,871
But knowing won't
bring him back.

331
00:22:59,405 --> 00:23:03,863
It's hard to accept so many unanswered
questions, but sometimes...

332
00:23:04,246 --> 00:23:06,550
No, you're right...

333
00:23:07,018 --> 00:23:08,652
Dr. Pittman.

334
00:23:09,578 --> 00:23:11,830
Yeah, this is really hard.

335
00:23:13,905 --> 00:23:16,493
You mind if I just take
a minute alone with...

336
00:23:17,767 --> 00:23:18,702
Dad?

337
00:23:20,047 --> 00:23:22,721
I'll be next door in my office.

338
00:23:50,808 --> 00:23:52,263
Masuka.

339
00:23:52,266 --> 00:23:53,712
Hey, it's Dexter Morgan.

340
00:23:53,907 --> 00:23:56,242
Dude, I know
your last name.

341
00:23:56,445 --> 00:23:58,980
I need a favor,
a DNA comparison.

342
00:23:59,126 --> 00:24:01,320
I thought you were away
with the girlfriend.

343
00:24:01,428 --> 00:24:03,170
What? She surfing
the Crimson wave?

344
00:24:03,248 --> 00:24:05,120
I'm just helping
out a local agency.

345
00:24:05,818 --> 00:24:08,492
I'm gonna send you
two blood samples.

346
00:24:08,556 --> 00:24:10,172
I need it A.S.A.P.

347
00:24:10,216 --> 00:24:11,843
Do a tox
screen, will you?

348
00:24:11,877 --> 00:24:14,983
Hey, Romeo, if this is your
idea of a romantic weekend,

349
00:24:15,116 --> 00:24:17,480
you're gonna be a bachelor
for a very long time.

350
00:24:17,606 --> 00:24:18,203
Yeah.

351
00:24:27,457 --> 00:24:30,363
Run another I.V.
Let's keep his blood levels volumized.

352
00:24:30,506 --> 00:24:32,051
What's his pressure?

353
00:24:32,057 --> 00:24:33,611
It's 80 and dropping.

354
00:24:33,747 --> 00:24:36,120
We may need to
do a belly tap.

355
00:24:36,126 --> 00:24:38,500
Hey, Dex.
Buddy, I'm here.

356
00:24:38,686 --> 00:24:40,370
- It hurts, dad.
- What happened?

357
00:24:40,606 --> 00:24:43,102
He tried to climb a fence
to get Debra's ball,

358
00:24:43,156 --> 00:24:44,900
but a dog chased after him,

359
00:24:44,925 --> 00:24:46,903
and he fell on a
wrought-iron post.

360
00:24:46,957 --> 00:24:48,253
Is he gonna be all right?

361
00:24:48,598 --> 00:24:50,193
We can keep him
stable for a while.

362
00:24:50,225 --> 00:24:52,943
But he's gonna need surgery to
repair some internal bleeding,

363
00:24:52,976 --> 00:24:53,972
and that's a problem.

364
00:24:54,005 --> 00:24:55,703
Can we talk over
here, please?

365
00:24:55,757 --> 00:24:57,343
Dex, I'll be right back.

366
00:24:57,488 --> 00:24:59,680
Hold your brother's
hand, sweetie.

367
00:25:00,658 --> 00:25:03,762
Okay, the complication is
with your son's blood type.

368
00:25:03,806 --> 00:25:05,350
I don't want to
talk about this.

369
00:25:05,385 --> 00:25:06,961
Why are you being like this?!

370
00:25:06,998 --> 00:25:09,350
You don't need to mention
that in front of anybody.

371
00:25:09,387 --> 00:25:11,002
Are you crazy?!
He could die.

372
00:25:11,047 --> 00:25:13,240
You got to do something quick.
You've got to go now.

373
00:25:17,707 --> 00:25:19,563
So, you heard the .38 go off

374
00:25:19,595 --> 00:25:21,441
before sergeant
Doakes' 9-millimeter.

375
00:25:21,638 --> 00:25:24,042
Then I went under the causeway,
and I saw the suspect...

376
00:25:24,075 --> 00:25:25,382
Mr. Bayard...

377
00:25:25,938 --> 00:25:28,200
Mr. Bayard on the ground,

378
00:25:28,326 --> 00:25:30,312
his gun lying next to him.

379
00:25:30,456 --> 00:25:32,452
And you're sure it was
Mr. Bayard's gun?

380
00:25:32,565 --> 00:25:34,671
Well, the .38 wasn't mine.

381
00:25:34,908 --> 00:25:37,252
And Sergeant Doakes had
his niner in his hands.

382
00:25:37,297 --> 00:25:38,902
Did you see Mr. Bayard
carrying the gun

383
00:25:38,958 --> 00:25:40,693
before the foot
chase began?

384
00:25:40,915 --> 00:25:42,550
Sergeant Doakes did.

385
00:25:42,686 --> 00:25:44,830
Did you see Mr. Bayard
acting suspiciously?

386
00:25:46,607 --> 00:25:48,803
Did you know Mr. Bayard
worked as a janitor?

387
00:25:48,826 --> 00:25:50,000
I --

388
00:25:50,405 --> 00:25:52,193
How the fuck
would I know that?

389
00:25:52,226 --> 00:25:53,900
Never got so much
as a parking ticket

390
00:25:53,948 --> 00:25:56,630
since he immigrated from
Haiti 15 years ago.

391
00:25:59,455 --> 00:26:02,273
He got a lot more than
that this time, didn't he?

392
00:26:08,606 --> 00:26:10,750
Are you sure you
heard the .38 go off

393
00:26:10,807 --> 00:26:13,090
before Sergeant
Doakes' 9-millimeter?

394
00:26:23,325 --> 00:26:26,471
Joe bought this house
outright in 1976,

395
00:26:26,607 --> 00:26:28,003
paid cash,

396
00:26:28,046 --> 00:26:29,600
no records before that.

397
00:26:29,646 --> 00:26:30,902
No records,

398
00:26:30,948 --> 00:26:32,931
no childhood photos...

399
00:26:33,308 --> 00:26:34,661
The guy was 60,

400
00:26:34,855 --> 00:26:37,151
but it's like his life
started when he was 30.

401
00:26:37,198 --> 00:26:38,602
You know, you're right.

402
00:26:38,647 --> 00:26:40,062
He's right.

403
00:26:40,106 --> 00:26:42,780
So, what happened
between years one and 29?

404
00:26:42,826 --> 00:26:45,401
Maybe he butchered
his entire family.

405
00:26:45,455 --> 00:26:46,303
Yeah...

406
00:26:46,506 --> 00:26:48,302
Or he walked out
on his two wives

407
00:26:48,357 --> 00:26:49,972
and a lot of bad debt.

408
00:26:50,017 --> 00:26:51,401
The guy was a loser, after all.

409
00:26:51,458 --> 00:26:53,691
Who else owns this
many bowling balls?

410
00:26:53,897 --> 00:26:55,530
What do you think, Dex?

411
00:26:56,278 --> 00:26:59,801
I think Joe spent
some time in prison,

412
00:27:00,176 --> 00:27:02,473
probably mixed with
some bad people.

413
00:27:02,798 --> 00:27:04,483
Maybe he had to hide from them.

414
00:27:04,665 --> 00:27:06,733
Whatever it was,
drugs were involved --

415
00:27:06,918 --> 00:27:08,700
Narcotics anonymous.

416
00:27:08,836 --> 00:27:10,003
Paul used to get these,

417
00:27:10,197 --> 00:27:12,492
except he never made it
past the welcome chip.

418
00:27:12,806 --> 00:27:15,250
Looks like Joe
was clean for...

419
00:27:15,285 --> 00:27:16,901
Let me guess --
30 years.

420
00:27:17,008 --> 00:27:18,421
Well, Joe said
no to the drugs,

421
00:27:18,458 --> 00:27:19,832
but not his rock 'n' roll.

422
00:27:19,868 --> 00:27:22,472
Nothing in his
collection post-1980.

423
00:27:22,955 --> 00:27:24,801
Got to love a purist.

424
00:27:42,245 --> 00:27:43,982
Oh, good.
Dancing.

425
00:28:36,166 --> 00:28:39,451
- Hello?
- Hey, babe. It's Paul.

426
00:28:41,906 --> 00:28:44,431
Just making sure dear Dexter

427
00:28:44,576 --> 00:28:47,373
is dealing decently
with his dead dad.

428
00:28:49,566 --> 00:28:50,701
We're fine.

429
00:28:50,805 --> 00:28:52,671
Everyone's fine, OK?

430
00:28:52,817 --> 00:28:55,112
- We'll see you on Monday.
- No, no, no.

431
00:28:55,158 --> 00:28:56,252
Talk to me.

432
00:28:56,356 --> 00:28:57,900
You having fun?

433
00:28:58,505 --> 00:28:59,800
'Cause I'm not.

434
00:28:59,957 --> 00:29:01,782
- Paul.
- I would have.

435
00:29:02,666 --> 00:29:05,373
I could have taken my
kids to the circus.

436
00:29:06,736 --> 00:29:09,032
We'd be eating
peanuts right now,

437
00:29:09,217 --> 00:29:11,193
stepping in elephant shit.

438
00:29:11,377 --> 00:29:13,773
Paul, this is not helping
my confidence in you.

439
00:29:13,956 --> 00:29:17,350
Oh, I think you've got enough
confidence for both of us.

440
00:29:17,457 --> 00:29:18,801
Look, if you want to work

441
00:29:18,846 --> 00:29:20,852
towards building more
visitation days, not less,

442
00:29:20,905 --> 00:29:23,200
you need to avoid this kind
of behavior right here.

443
00:29:27,897 --> 00:29:30,070
Now, I think you
might just want

444
00:29:30,095 --> 00:29:31,753
to politely hang up.

445
00:29:36,795 --> 00:29:37,671
Okay.

446
00:29:39,525 --> 00:29:40,273
You're right.

447
00:29:41,517 --> 00:29:42,401
I'm sorry.

448
00:29:44,066 --> 00:29:46,221
You have a great weekend.

449
00:29:57,087 --> 00:29:58,962
<i>A secret life --</i>

450
00:29:59,106 --> 00:30:01,411
<i>The only thing Joe
and I have in common.</i>

451
00:30:02,106 --> 00:30:04,640
<i>There's nothing else in
this house to connect us.</i>

452
00:30:05,338 --> 00:30:06,611
Hiding out?

453
00:30:09,446 --> 00:30:10,663
Cleaning up.

454
00:30:14,427 --> 00:30:17,243
I can only imagine what
you're going through.

455
00:30:17,847 --> 00:30:19,921
A lot of
lemon-fresh joy.

456
00:30:20,467 --> 00:30:21,913
You joke.

457
00:30:22,175 --> 00:30:24,003
It's good defense,
by the way.

458
00:30:24,016 --> 00:30:25,842
Thank you.
I think.

459
00:30:25,885 --> 00:30:27,193
Still,

460
00:30:27,358 --> 00:30:29,870
the possibility has got
to be weighing on you.

461
00:30:29,946 --> 00:30:31,513
What possibility?

462
00:30:31,707 --> 00:30:33,101
That Joe

463
00:30:33,225 --> 00:30:35,051
could actually
be your dad.

464
00:30:35,107 --> 00:30:36,602
The only way
that's a possibility

465
00:30:36,647 --> 00:30:39,200
is if Harry was wrong.
And, uh,

466
00:30:39,356 --> 00:30:41,700
that's just not possible.

467
00:30:42,875 --> 00:30:44,620
Or he lied.

468
00:30:46,885 --> 00:30:49,833
Don't you worry, little man.
You're not gonna feel a thing.

469
00:30:49,878 --> 00:30:52,740
I thought there was a problem --
you know, the blood?

470
00:30:52,928 --> 00:30:54,041
Your dad fixed it.

471
00:30:54,235 --> 00:30:57,663
See, you have a very special
blood type -- A.B. negative.

472
00:30:57,807 --> 00:30:59,972
It's hard to come by,
and our supply was low.

473
00:31:00,005 --> 00:31:02,311
But your dad knew somebody
with blood just like yours.

474
00:31:02,346 --> 00:31:03,750
You're very lucky.

475
00:31:03,987 --> 00:31:06,031
- Can I have a moment with my son?
- Yeah.

476
00:31:06,305 --> 00:31:07,501
Hey, Dex.

477
00:31:07,776 --> 00:31:09,432
Everything's gonna be fine.

478
00:31:09,708 --> 00:31:11,201
You'll be good as new.

479
00:31:11,235 --> 00:31:12,600
I will?

480
00:31:12,755 --> 00:31:14,351
Hey, would
I lie to you?

481
00:31:19,105 --> 00:31:21,101
When my father was dying,

482
00:31:21,207 --> 00:31:23,422
he just asked me
for one thing --

483
00:31:23,688 --> 00:31:26,932
Deber?a ser
un hombre honesto.

484
00:31:30,167 --> 00:31:31,761
"Be an honest man."

485
00:31:35,605 --> 00:31:37,143
That's all he asked.

486
00:31:39,636 --> 00:31:41,682
I made him that promise,

487
00:31:41,688 --> 00:31:43,730
and that's why I'm a cop.

488
00:31:47,938 --> 00:31:50,240
Now this Haitian
man is dead,

489
00:31:50,845 --> 00:31:52,541
and I don't know why,

490
00:31:53,566 --> 00:31:56,012
but I know it ain't right.

491
00:31:58,966 --> 00:32:01,271
But if I talk...

492
00:32:01,678 --> 00:32:04,371
I'll be a rat to
the whole precinct.

493
00:32:05,337 --> 00:32:08,151
- But if I lie --
- Hold up.

494
00:32:18,605 --> 00:32:19,903
Go ahead.

495
00:32:34,558 --> 00:32:38,303
The blood spatter doesn't
match Doakes' report.

496
00:32:42,218 --> 00:32:43,103
Also...

497
00:32:47,357 --> 00:32:51,211
...I heard Doakes' 9-millimeter
go off before the .38.

498
00:32:51,895 --> 00:32:55,091
- But he must have had good cause.
- So Doakes fired first?

499
00:33:01,425 --> 00:33:03,063
Doakes fired first.

500
00:33:14,997 --> 00:33:16,861
I hope tuna's all right.

501
00:33:17,098 --> 00:33:18,881
Mmm, love me a little mercury.

502
00:33:20,317 --> 00:33:21,601
That's Dexter's.

503
00:33:21,638 --> 00:33:24,212
Oh, he's out stealing garbage-can
space from the neighbors.

504
00:33:24,246 --> 00:33:26,070
Criminal -- I like it.

505
00:33:26,167 --> 00:33:27,633
It's the station.

506
00:33:28,577 --> 00:33:30,212
Morgan here.

507
00:33:31,257 --> 00:33:32,300
Wait.

