00:33:32,358 --> 00:33:34,650
Did I call the hot
Morgan by mistake?

509
00:33:35,167 --> 00:33:36,521
Freudian.

510
00:33:36,705 --> 00:33:39,540
My subconscious
has been exposed.

511
00:33:39,578 --> 00:33:41,850
Well, zip it up and tell
me what's going on.

512
00:33:41,886 --> 00:33:43,042
I got the results.

513
00:33:43,106 --> 00:33:44,813
On Doakes' shooting?
Has he been cleared?

514
00:33:44,865 --> 00:33:46,402
On the DNA test.

515
00:33:47,507 --> 00:33:48,801
What DNA test?

516
00:34:09,207 --> 00:34:10,850
You trusted dad
your entire life,

517
00:34:10,905 --> 00:34:12,802
so why question him now?

518
00:34:15,306 --> 00:34:17,003
Am I missing something?

519
00:34:18,855 --> 00:34:21,002
DNA test?

520
00:34:22,407 --> 00:34:24,003
Masuka called?

521
00:34:24,058 --> 00:34:26,300
Your biological
father was dead.

522
00:34:26,357 --> 00:34:27,551
Dad told us that.

523
00:34:27,607 --> 00:34:28,752
I remember.

524
00:34:28,855 --> 00:34:31,102
So, the DNA came back negative?

525
00:34:33,228 --> 00:34:34,903
It was a match.

526
00:34:36,207 --> 00:34:38,703
Joe Driscoll was your bio dad.

527
00:34:51,225 --> 00:34:52,390
Interesting.

528
00:34:54,796 --> 00:34:56,953
Do you think dad...

529
00:34:57,507 --> 00:34:58,752
lied?

530
00:35:00,117 --> 00:35:02,331
I think he might have
known Joe was here...

531
00:35:04,177 --> 00:35:06,953
...Five hours up
I-95 my whole life.

532
00:35:07,365 --> 00:35:09,461
Well, he must have had
a damn good reason.

533
00:35:10,205 --> 00:35:12,453
And I'm not gonna let some
guy you didn't even know

534
00:35:12,508 --> 00:35:14,000
draw him into question.

535
00:35:14,157 --> 00:35:15,753
Deb, I'm not
questioning anything.

536
00:35:16,906 --> 00:35:19,501
That's why you got
a tox screen, too.

537
00:35:25,158 --> 00:35:26,590
I need to clear my head.

538
00:35:28,825 --> 00:35:30,423
Where are your car keys?

539
00:35:35,735 --> 00:35:37,371
Deb, I ordered the
tox screen because

540
00:35:37,408 --> 00:35:38,960
Joe had no history
of heart disease

541
00:35:38,996 --> 00:35:40,540
and the coroner's
report was inept.

542
00:35:40,575 --> 00:35:41,402
You did it

543
00:35:41,438 --> 00:35:43,752
because, for some reason,
he is important to you.

544
00:35:43,785 --> 00:35:45,353
It was professional curiosity.

545
00:35:45,386 --> 00:35:46,750
Then you will be
professionally glad to know

546
00:35:46,806 --> 00:35:48,802
that the only
toxin in his system

547
00:35:48,857 --> 00:35:50,101
was a sedative,

548
00:35:50,208 --> 00:35:51,952
which he probably took to...

549
00:35:52,167 --> 00:35:54,232
I don't know, sleep.

550
00:35:54,756 --> 00:35:56,150
That would surprise me.

551
00:35:56,555 --> 00:35:58,253
Joe was 30 years sober,

552
00:35:58,287 --> 00:35:59,382
I haven't found
anything stronger

553
00:35:59,408 --> 00:36:01,100
than Advil in his
medicine cabinet.

554
00:36:03,795 --> 00:36:07,041
It wouldn't be the first time an
addict fell off the wagon, Rita.

555
00:36:07,306 --> 00:36:09,001
Or someone slipped
him the sedative

556
00:36:09,056 --> 00:36:11,403
so he wouldn't struggle when he
was injected with something.

557
00:36:11,906 --> 00:36:13,372
Like?

558
00:36:13,406 --> 00:36:15,002
Diabetic insulin.

559
00:36:15,475 --> 00:36:17,251
It can cause cardiac arrest.

560
00:36:17,407 --> 00:36:18,552
We've seen it before.

561
00:36:18,608 --> 00:36:20,003
It's nearly impossible
to detect

562
00:36:20,057 --> 00:36:21,552
unless you can find
a point of injection,

563
00:36:21,587 --> 00:36:23,190
which I wasn't looking for,
but if I had a chance

564
00:36:23,258 --> 00:36:25,353
- to examinate the body, I --
- Jesus Christ!

565
00:36:25,557 --> 00:36:27,652
He's not even your family!

566
00:36:28,966 --> 00:36:30,973
Mom and dad were.

567
00:36:31,156 --> 00:36:32,613
I am.

568
00:36:35,237 --> 00:36:37,583
Are you gonna start
questioning me now?

569
00:36:37,726 --> 00:36:39,171
You? Why would I --

570
00:36:40,008 --> 00:36:42,782
Joe Driscoll was obviously
bad fucking news,

571
00:36:42,816 --> 00:36:45,802
which is why dad didn't want
you to know anything about him!

572
00:36:45,877 --> 00:36:48,102
Doesn't that matter to you?!

573
00:36:51,108 --> 00:36:53,150
I don't know what
you want from me.

574
00:36:59,316 --> 00:37:01,510
I want what dad wanted.

575
00:37:02,035 --> 00:37:04,471
I want nothing to
do with this guy.

576
00:37:05,047 --> 00:37:07,442
Let's just finish packing
up this crappy house

577
00:37:07,477 --> 00:37:09,580
and walk the fuck away!

578
00:37:10,125 --> 00:37:12,470
All right. That sounds like
a good plan. Okay?

579
00:37:29,205 --> 00:37:31,500
<i>I guess I understand
why Deb is upset.</i>

580
00:37:31,537 --> 00:37:33,131
<i>We both idolized Harry,</i>

581
00:37:33,168 --> 00:37:35,153
<i>lived by what he taught us...</i>

582
00:37:35,837 --> 00:37:37,301
<i>Though Deb never
had to be taught</i>

583
00:37:37,337 --> 00:37:39,203
<i>not to kill innocent people.</i>

584
00:37:42,287 --> 00:37:43,700
<i>That's why she
doesn't understand</i>

585
00:37:43,745 --> 00:37:45,102
<i>why I need to know.</i>

586
00:37:50,505 --> 00:37:51,801
Howdy, neighbor.

587
00:37:51,958 --> 00:37:53,232
Let me get that for you.

588
00:37:54,307 --> 00:37:55,802
Well, thank you.

589
00:37:55,906 --> 00:37:57,102
I was just wondering --

590
00:37:57,158 --> 00:38:00,152
Did you happen to notice any
visitors over at Joe's last week?

591
00:38:00,467 --> 00:38:01,893
Visitors?

592
00:38:01,958 --> 00:38:03,283
Oh, I'm not sure.

593
00:38:03,466 --> 00:38:06,473
I'm just wondering if he
has any outstanding bills --

594
00:38:06,665 --> 00:38:10,190
A gardener, maybe, or
a delivery person, repairman?

595
00:38:10,888 --> 00:38:13,561
Well, come to think of it,
there was a, um,

596
00:38:13,748 --> 00:38:16,143
cable repairman here last week.

597
00:38:16,328 --> 00:38:17,591
He was polite.

598
00:38:17,778 --> 00:38:20,723
But, you know,
he couldn't fix my TV antenna.

599
00:38:21,325 --> 00:38:23,150
You remember what
he looked like?

600
00:38:25,236 --> 00:38:27,910
Well, he had dark hair...

601
00:38:28,328 --> 00:38:31,960
Average height --
Normal, I suppose.

602
00:38:36,257 --> 00:38:39,063
I did some checking on our
suspect Jacques Bayard.

603
00:38:39,545 --> 00:38:41,602
You lending I.A. a hand?

604
00:38:41,976 --> 00:38:44,402
I just like to know what's
going on in my department.

605
00:38:44,976 --> 00:38:46,803
And what is going on?

606
00:38:46,995 --> 00:38:49,203
Turns out Mr. Bayard
changed his name

607
00:38:49,238 --> 00:38:50,560
when he immigrated here.

608
00:38:51,028 --> 00:38:52,950
Used to be Rene Thibault,

609
00:38:53,307 --> 00:38:56,310
a former officer in
the Haitian military.

610
00:38:57,705 --> 00:38:59,902
Didn't your tour in
the army include some...

611
00:39:00,007 --> 00:39:02,203
special op in Haiti?

612
00:39:03,835 --> 00:39:04,803
Right.

613
00:39:04,958 --> 00:39:07,202
"Special" means you
don't talk about it.

614
00:39:08,288 --> 00:39:10,702
But I know you've heard as
many horror stories as I have

615
00:39:10,756 --> 00:39:12,223
about what went
on down there

616
00:39:12,287 --> 00:39:13,992
with those death squads.

617
00:39:15,057 --> 00:39:16,873
What were they called?

618
00:39:17,626 --> 00:39:19,831
Tonton Macoute.

619
00:39:20,296 --> 00:39:22,702
Yeah, "the bogeymen."

620
00:39:24,956 --> 00:39:27,201
They did a lot of
terrible things,

621
00:39:27,577 --> 00:39:29,311
killed a lot of people.

622
00:39:32,916 --> 00:39:36,110
They made mothers carry the
heads of their dead sons,

623
00:39:36,438 --> 00:39:39,773
forced fathers to
rape their daughters.

624
00:39:40,006 --> 00:39:43,102
They tied cinder blocks around
people's necks and drowned them

625
00:39:43,296 --> 00:39:44,901
and put mutilated
bodies in trees

626
00:39:44,947 --> 00:39:47,513
and killed anybody who
tried to take them down.

627
00:39:50,775 --> 00:39:53,073
This man, Jacques Bayard,

628
00:39:53,656 --> 00:39:55,851
if he did those things...

629
00:39:57,176 --> 00:39:59,672
he deserved a lot
worse than he got.

630
00:40:06,908 --> 00:40:08,553
Don't worry, James.

631
00:40:08,606 --> 00:40:10,240
It'll be over soon.

632
00:40:14,726 --> 00:40:16,362
I know it will.

633
00:40:36,007 --> 00:40:39,623
<i>If Joe was shot up with insulin,
there will be an injection welt...</i>

634
00:40:40,186 --> 00:40:43,242
<i>Maybe between his
toes or in a freckle.</i>

635
00:40:43,475 --> 00:40:45,253
<i>If it's there, I'll find it.</i>

636
00:40:49,945 --> 00:40:51,582
Small towns.

637
00:41:15,665 --> 00:41:19,711
Come on, Dr. Pittman, which
crematorium did you send Joe to?

638
00:41:38,877 --> 00:41:41,771
Hey! You! stop! Come on!

639
00:42:03,468 --> 00:42:04,421
Get in!

640
00:42:13,807 --> 00:42:15,091
Heard you sneak out.

641
00:42:15,605 --> 00:42:17,412
Took a guess where
you were headed.

642
00:42:18,598 --> 00:42:20,372
Figuring I'd need a ride?

643
00:42:20,408 --> 00:42:22,040
Figured I could
talk you out of it.

644
00:42:22,276 --> 00:42:24,033
No such luck, huh?

645
00:42:24,725 --> 00:42:26,413
Deb will be delighted.

646
00:42:26,645 --> 00:42:29,370
As far as I know,
you went out for a walk.

647
00:42:34,355 --> 00:42:36,751
Jesus, Dex,
did you steal something?

648
00:42:37,975 --> 00:42:39,920
Well, my fingerprints
were all over it.

649
00:42:40,037 --> 00:42:42,630
I figured it was prudent to
get rid of the evidence.

650
00:42:42,807 --> 00:42:44,682
It's just a box of ashes.

651
00:42:46,487 --> 00:42:49,731
- Joe was cremated, then?
- Yep.

652
00:42:51,007 --> 00:42:52,503
Guess you weren't
able to find out

653
00:42:52,535 --> 00:42:54,533
if he was injected
with anything.

654
00:42:54,757 --> 00:42:55,682
No.

655
00:42:58,716 --> 00:43:01,580
- What are you gonna do with him?
- I don't know.

656
00:43:05,418 --> 00:43:07,292
Hmm, dumpster?

657
00:43:09,096 --> 00:43:11,110
I have a better idea.

658
00:43:26,556 --> 00:43:27,613
You know...

659
00:43:29,847 --> 00:43:31,671
No matter what Harry said,

660
00:43:32,238 --> 00:43:34,393
no matter what Deb thinks,

661
00:43:35,138 --> 00:43:36,902
that's your father.

662
00:43:37,108 --> 00:43:39,082
Cardboard box?

663
00:43:39,266 --> 00:43:40,902
I know you don't want
to acknowledge it,

664
00:43:40,938 --> 00:43:43,741
which is why you're running around,
breaking and entering,

665
00:43:43,776 --> 00:43:45,842
searching for some killer.

666
00:43:47,007 --> 00:43:48,701
But you took that

667
00:43:48,807 --> 00:43:50,602
because there's a part of you

668
00:43:51,205 --> 00:43:53,402
that knows that this...

669
00:43:55,068 --> 00:43:56,663
that box...

670
00:43:57,607 --> 00:43:59,903
is your real father.

671
00:44:18,207 --> 00:44:19,401
My father.

672
00:44:35,285 --> 00:44:37,022
Sounds strange.

673
00:44:38,496 --> 00:44:39,530
I know.

674
00:45:40,366 --> 00:45:42,102
You all right?

675
00:45:43,495 --> 00:45:45,402
I was just getting some air.

676
00:45:49,888 --> 00:45:53,602
Oh, hey, I found something
in Joe's closet.

677
00:45:54,007 --> 00:45:55,751
It's just a bunch of papers.

678
00:45:56,065 --> 00:45:57,851
They're over there.

679
00:46:12,668 --> 00:46:14,453
Any clues?

680
00:46:24,577 --> 00:46:25,502
Hey, buddy.

681
00:46:26,797 --> 00:46:29,001
- How you feeling?
- Good.

682
00:46:29,375 --> 00:46:32,100
It kind of itches,
but they have ice cream here.

683
00:46:32,606 --> 00:46:34,060
Life's a trade-off.

684
00:46:34,318 --> 00:46:35,700
What are you making there?

685
00:46:35,905 --> 00:46:37,352
A thank-you card.

686
00:46:38,278 --> 00:46:41,230
See? The nurse brought me
the crayons and everything.

687
00:46:41,418 --> 00:46:42,750
Who's it for?

688
00:46:43,058 --> 00:46:47,663
Well, she said I should thank
the man who gave me the blood.

689
00:46:47,808 --> 00:46:48,803
I mean,

690
00:46:49,006 --> 00:46:52,500
that's normal, right,
giving thank-you cards?

691
00:46:58,158 --> 00:46:59,600
Yes, it is.

692
00:47:01,176 --> 00:47:02,720
It's just that he's gone.

693
00:47:03,646 --> 00:47:05,523
And we won't be
seeing him again.

694
00:47:06,458 --> 00:47:08,102
I'm sorry.

695
00:47:08,438 --> 00:47:10,121
That's all right.

696
00:47:10,156 --> 00:47:12,701
It doesn't really
mean anything.

697
00:47:21,375 --> 00:47:23,083
Yeah, it does.

698
00:47:24,355 --> 00:47:26,200
You keep drawing, son.

699
00:47:26,455 --> 00:47:28,252
I'll make sure it finds him.

700
00:47:29,447 --> 00:47:30,850
Okay.

701
00:47:48,657 --> 00:47:50,753
You had the case dropped?

702
00:47:51,126 --> 00:47:52,291
Excuse me.

703
00:47:55,767 --> 00:47:57,782
I.A. dropped Doakes' case.

704
00:47:57,906 --> 00:47:59,313
Do you seriously
think I have any say

705
00:47:59,345 --> 00:48:00,682
over what I.A. does?

706
00:48:00,717 --> 00:48:02,190
I put everything
on the line.

707
00:48:02,197 --> 00:48:03,671
I told I.A. the truth,

708
00:48:03,817 --> 00:48:05,750
and there's a lot of
evidence to back that up.

709
00:48:05,787 --> 00:48:07,423
What the hell happened?

710
00:48:07,607 --> 00:48:09,451
Maria! I deserve to know.

711
00:48:09,506 --> 00:48:11,712
All I know is that
I.A. got a call

712
00:48:11,747 --> 00:48:13,101
from an agency
in Washington.

713
00:48:13,208 --> 00:48:15,172
- What agency?
- I'm guessing military.

714
00:48:15,206 --> 00:48:16,803
They said the
case involved some --

715
00:48:16,837 --> 00:48:18,932
sensitive foreign-relations issues,

716
00:48:19,007 --> 00:48:21,203
so they were gonna
handle it from there.

717
00:48:21,228 --> 00:48:22,453
They disappeared it.

718
00:48:22,485 --> 00:48:24,052
I always knew Doakes
had a history with them.

719
00:48:24,107 --> 00:48:25,601
I figured Special Forces,

720
00:48:25,646 --> 00:48:26,850
but this kind of reach --

721
00:48:26,885 --> 00:48:28,101
You think it was
black ops, CIA?

722
00:48:28,207 --> 00:48:29,302
Maybe.

723
00:48:31,847 --> 00:48:32,873
Probably.

724
00:48:33,937 --> 00:48:36,473
And I ratted him out.
Jesus Christ.

725
00:48:36,606 --> 00:48:37,600
Angel...

726
00:48:38,205 --> 00:48:40,303
You did what you
thought was right.

727
00:48:46,308 --> 00:48:47,803
Squeak, squeak.

728
00:48:48,405 --> 00:48:49,951
Do you have a problem?

729
00:48:50,227 --> 00:48:51,200
Officer Benson,

730
00:48:52,548 --> 00:48:54,802
you just bumped
into your superior.

731
00:48:56,307 --> 00:48:59,801
I believe you owe detective
Batista an apology!

732
00:49:02,068 --> 00:49:03,090
Yes, sir.

733
00:49:05,406 --> 00:49:06,902
I'm sorry, sir.

734
00:49:45,208 --> 00:49:46,802
I know I should
be sorry that

735
00:49:46,846 --> 00:49:48,752
we met under these
circumstances,

736
00:49:49,005 --> 00:49:50,400
but truthfully,

737
00:49:50,608 --> 00:49:52,702
I think it was the best
way to get to know you.

738
00:49:55,795 --> 00:49:58,090
Realtor says you
won't get much for it.

739
00:50:01,618 --> 00:50:03,252
More than if I kept it.

740
00:50:04,257 --> 00:50:05,902
Are we good?

741
00:50:10,386 --> 00:50:11,740
We're fine.

742
00:50:17,707 --> 00:50:19,203
All right.

743
00:50:19,476 --> 00:50:21,180
I'll see you back
at the station.

744
00:50:36,808 --> 00:50:39,202
Cable repair man.

745
00:50:40,097 --> 00:50:43,391
Wait! Wait!
No, no, don't go.

746
00:50:43,718 --> 00:50:45,170
Wait!

747
00:50:45,408 --> 00:50:47,400
Please, I want to
ask you something.

748
00:50:49,806 --> 00:50:50,881
Wait!

749
00:50:53,288 --> 00:50:55,160
Alone again.

750
00:50:56,005 --> 00:50:57,451
Finally.

751
00:51:00,548 --> 00:51:01,663
You know what?

752
00:51:04,345 --> 00:51:05,893
I'm glad you were here.

753
00:51:06,766 --> 00:51:08,742
Thought you would be.

754
00:51:14,105 --> 00:51:16,642
The cable repairman --

755
00:51:17,658 --> 00:51:21,352
Did he say anything
about my TV antenna?!

756
00:51:23,908 --> 00:51:24,900
No!

757
00:52:01,015 --> 00:52:02,463
Rita, it's me.

758
00:52:06,486 --> 00:52:07,751
They're asleep.

759
00:52:07,807 --> 00:52:09,701
Yeah, well,
I should have been here, okay?

760
00:52:09,757 --> 00:52:11,303
It's late,
and you're drunk

761
00:52:11,357 --> 00:52:13,433
and you can't keep coming
by here unannounced.

762
00:52:13,477 --> 00:52:16,263
You don't call the shots, okay?

763
00:52:16,808 --> 00:52:18,501
Paul, I want you to leave.

764
00:52:18,536 --> 00:52:20,350
I don't give a
fuck what you want.

765
00:52:20,407 --> 00:52:21,953
I want my fucking kids!

766
00:52:21,988 --> 00:52:23,153
You're gonna scare them.

767
00:52:23,355 --> 00:52:24,501
They don't want to see me?

768
00:52:24,538 --> 00:52:27,601
Those kids are gonna remember who
the head of this fucking family is.

769
00:52:30,505 --> 00:52:31,900
You're right.

770
00:52:32,306 --> 00:52:33,700
I've been awful.

771
00:52:34,155 --> 00:52:37,260
I just didn't realize I
was hurting you so much.

772
00:52:37,507 --> 00:52:39,303
But I can make
it up to you.

773
00:52:39,707 --> 00:52:41,601
Let me try.

774
00:52:56,707 --> 00:52:58,200
Where are you going?

775
00:52:59,366 --> 00:53:01,990
Want to play rough? Huh?
Is that what you want?

776
00:53:02,178 --> 00:53:03,300
No!
No!

777
00:53:04,095 --> 00:53:05,601
Fucking whore.

778
00:53:05,697 --> 00:53:08,603
Come on.
Come on!

779
00:53:18,046 --> 00:53:20,290
Wake up. Wake up. Come on.

780
00:53:59,408 --> 00:54:01,501
<i>I had a father...</i>

781
00:54:02,216 --> 00:54:05,011
<i>Someone other than
Harry who called me son.</i>

782
00:54:06,247 --> 00:54:08,802
<i>The thought never
even occurred to me.</i>

783
00:54:09,528 --> 00:54:11,402
<i>Harry was all I needed.</i>

784
00:54:12,605 --> 00:54:15,143
<i>It was Harry who always
had the answers.</i>

785
00:54:16,065 --> 00:54:19,852
<i>He knew who was good,
bad, safe...</i>

786
00:54:20,435 --> 00:54:22,330
<i>And dangerous.</i>

787
00:54:22,907 --> 00:54:25,142
<i>I built my life on Harry's code.</i>

788
00:54:25,208 --> 00:54:26,602
<i>I lived by it.</i>

789
00:54:27,705 --> 00:54:29,471
<i>But Harry lied.</i>

790
00:54:29,887 --> 00:54:31,622
<i>Why would he do that?</i>

791
00:54:31,906 --> 00:54:33,871
<i>What else don't I know?</i>

792
00:54:34,386 --> 00:54:37,913
<i>My concrete foundation is
turning to shifting sand.</i>

793
00:54:38,337 --> 00:54:40,010
<i>Maybe Rudy was right --</i>

794
00:54:40,347 --> 00:54:42,692
<i>You never can
truly know anyone.</i>

